---
description: OpenAI integration best practices — API key handling, retry, timeouts, prompt design, structured output, and cost control. Apply to Java files that call the OpenAI API.
globs: **/*.java
---

## Credentials
- API key must come from environment variable or Spring config — never hardcode or log it
- Use `@Value("${openai.api-key}")` or a `@ConfigurationProperties` class — never inline the string
- Exclude API key from all log output and `toString()` methods

## Resilience
- All OpenAI calls must have a timeout configured on the HTTP client (recommended: 30s read timeout)
- Retry on `429 Too Many Requests` with exponential backoff — use Resilience4j or Spring Retry
- Retry on `5xx` transient errors with a max of 3 attempts
- Always handle `OpenAIException` at the service boundary — never let it propagate to the controller raw

## Transaction boundaries
- Never call the OpenAI API inside a `@Transactional` method
- If you need to persist results of an AI call, call OpenAI first, then open a transaction to persist

## Prompt design
- Prompts must not be unbounded — always set a `max_tokens` or equivalent limit
- User-supplied content injected into a prompt must be sanitized and bounded in length
- System prompts belong in config or resource files — not hardcoded in Java strings
- Document the token budget for each prompt in a comment: expected input tokens + max output tokens

## Structured output
- Prefer structured output (JSON mode or response_format) over parsing free-text responses
- The Java type used for deserialization must match the schema exactly — validate on startup if possible
- Handle `null` fields in the response gracefully — the model may omit optional fields

## Cost control
- Use the cheapest model that meets accuracy requirements — document the model choice and why
- Batch requests where the API supports it
- Log token usage (`prompt_tokens`, `completion_tokens`) at DEBUG level for cost monitoring
- Do not call the API in a loop without a circuit breaker or rate limit guard
